## Overview
KoboToolbox is an open-source platform for collecting, managing, and visualizing data in challenging environments.

## Purpose
It offers intuitive usability, tailored for efficient data collection without extensive technical training. Designed for challenging environments like humanitarian crises, it supports offline use on affordable mobile devices while providing advanced data management features.

## How it works
KoboToolbox allows users to design surveys or data collection forms using its intuitive interface, share them with innovators whether online or offline, collect and manage data on the platform, analyze data, and present findings using tools, visualizations, and presentation features.

## Requirements
Basic knowledge of digital platforms and familiarity with survey design and data collection methods; availability of internet access and mobile devices for data collection, as well as computers for data management and analysis; adherence to ethical guidelines and regulations governing research data collection and participant privacy; training sessions or resources to ensure users understand how to effectively utilize features for data collection and analysis.

## Reflections
Ensure survey design and data collection methods align closely with the research objectives; respect participant confidentiality and privacy - all participants should be informed of purpose and use of data collected; continuously evaluate and refine survey design and data collection methods based on feedback and insights gained.

## Related methods (if any)
KoboToolbox is often used in conjunction with other social innovation methods, such as:

* (Community) Asset Mapping
* Collective Intelligence
* Data Visualisation
* Ethnography
* Solutions Mapping

## License
Free or open-source.

## Examples
KoboToolbox has been used by various organizations and researchers to collect data in challenging environments. For example, the UNDP Mauritius and Seychelles Accelerator Lab used KoboToolbox to conduct a survey on youth in tourism across three islands.
